eveal the concurrent interrelation of the three moments of capital. The book's literary readings, meanwhile, make vivid the uneven texture and experience of capitalist modernity at large. Analyzing formally and thematically diverse novels—works by Fiston Mwanza Mujila, Marlon James, Jennifer Egan, Eugene Lim, Rafael Chirbes, Neel Mukherjee, Rachel Kushner, and others—Jelly-Schapiro evinces the different patterns of feeling and consciousness that register, and hypothesize a way beyond, the contradictions of capital. This book develops a new conceptual key for the mapping of contemporary theory, world literature, and global capital itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCapitalism in literature2DLC. 0aCritical theory2DLC. 0aFictiony21st centuryxHistory and criticism2DLC. 0aPostcolonialism2DLC. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aMarxism.  acapitalism.  acomparative literature.  aexpanded reproduction.  apostcolonial theory.  aprimitive accumulation.  asynthetic dispossession.  aworld literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023 Englishz978311131918608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023z9783111318264oZDB-23-DSP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363544940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503635449423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503635449/original  a978-3-11-079132-7  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-